post_text:
WC Parents and Students-

Just a reminder that all students will be required to wear a facial covering as long as WCPS remains in Phase 4. Just a few reminders about facial coverings:
1. May be disposable masks.
2. May be cloth "appropriate" masks.
3. May be gaiters.

WCPS will be providing all students will masks if needed.

1. Disposable masks must be thrown away each day.
2. Cloth masks and gaiters should be washed or cleaned daily.

Face shields are not considered a proper facial covering by the Health Department, but however, will be required if your student can not medically tolerate a mask.
Bandanas are not considered a proper facial covering at school by the Health Department.
Any other covering not acceptable by the Health Department.

Facial Covering Medical Opt. out forms are available on our website.

Please contact the school if you have any questions. As the norm, some of these requirements may change as we move through the fall.

Staff are working hard to provide students with opportunities to social distance, go outside, and take mask breaks.

WC PRIDE

COOKING MATTERS AT HOME:

WEDNESDAY, JUNE 17 FROM 2:00 - 3:00 P.M.

Sign up for the free Cooking Matters at Home: Snacking Online Workshop, scheduled Wednesday, June 17th from 2:00-3:00 pm. We will talk about healthy snacks that families can prepare and eat together at home. Kids are welcome to participate or you can print out activity sheets for them by clicking here! There will be recipe demonstrations and we will talk about making snacks from the foods you already have in your fridge and pantry. If you would like to “cook-along” with us, have the following ingredients on hand:
your favorite yogurt
fruit (fresh, frozen, canned, or dried)
cereal/granola, and nuts/seeds
flour tortilla
your favorite apple
nut butter
Call 1231-924-3073 to register, space is limited! Join us on any device with an internet connection. Participants will qualify for a free reusable grocery bag with fruits and vegetables!

TOTAL TREK QUEST FOR FALL 2020

TTQ is a fun, high energy program designed exclusively for male-identified students in 3rd-5th grade! Using a substance use prevention curriculum, TTQ combines strength &
stretching exercises with training for a 5K. Boys in this program will develop positive peer relationships and feel a part of a team, while working towards achieving individual
goals. Additional practice activities focus on developing a healthy lifestyle, social/relationship skills, how to make healthy decisions, and developing a sense of self.

Sign up for the free Cooking Matters at Home:

Snacking Online Workshop, scheduled Wednesday, June 17th from 2:00-3:00 pm.

We will talk about healthy snacks that families can prepare and eat together at home. Kids are welcome to participate or you can print out activity sheets for them by clicking here! There will be recipe demonstrations and we will talk about making snacks from the foods you already have in your fridge and pantry. If you would like to “cook-along” with us, have the following ingredients on hand:

• your favorite yogurt
• fruit (fresh, frozen, canned, or dried)
• cereal/granola, and nuts/seeds
• flour tortilla
• your favorite apple
• nut butter

Call 1231-924-3073 to register, space is limited! Join us on any device with an internet connection. Participants will qualify for a free reusable grocery bag with fruits and vegetables!

TTQ Summer 2020

Join us for the first ever TTQ summer program! TTQ Summer 2020 kicks off virtually, with in person meet-ups in July and August if possible. TTQ Summer is open to all incoming 3rd - outgoing 5th grade boys and male-identifying individuals, along with their family members!

The program begins the week of June 15 and ends with a virtual 5k the weekend of August 15.

TTQ Summer program includes: Virtual game night kickoff event Nine weeks of 5k training and experiential learning activities that focus on building coping and resilience skills, making healthy choices, and strengthening mental health Live/recorded runs and activities Weekly support forums A culminating virtual 5k at the end of the season support for ttq summer provided by:

TTQ Summer registration:
raceplanner.com/register/index/TTQSummer registration fees: $25 per child - Scholarships are available by contacting Brandon at bmelnyk@arborcircle.org or 616-450-4651

post_text:
May 19, 2020

As we get closer to our new dates to celebrate the Class of 2020, we wanted to let the community know how they could support if they would like to do so!

1. On the day of the CRUZE, B103.9 radio station will play the names of our Seniors at a specified time during the CRUZE. If local businesses would like to support this and help advertise in advance, you can contact Jen Theodore at B1039bigrapids@gmail.com. They will be running ads that announce your business name leading up to the June 6th broadcast.

2. We will be honoring the Class of 2020 on our electronic sign and the scoreboard on Thursday, May 21st - (which was the originally scheduled graduation date.) Seniors! If you want to "see your name in lights" drive by the High School on Thursday! We will run the names again on June 6th and on July 23rd.

3. On June 6th, have your yard or business decorated to celebrate our Seniors. The CRUZE route will be in town and will be released on May 28th.

Again, we want to thank the White Cloud community for all you have done to support the Class of 2020.

Senior Class Advisors

To the Class and Families of 2020:

With all the circumstances and unknowns out there related to COVID-19. I wanted to remind you that you are NOT forgotten. COVID-19 has taken away some of our traditional timelines, but we are still planning a Class of 2020 Graduation Ceremony in July or early August 2020, if permitted by the State of Michigan. I know this is a difficult time but hang in there. We are here to support you and celebrate the accomplishments you have earned. More information to come in the next few weeks.

WC PRIDE!!!!

Ed Canning
White Cloud Public Schools
Superintendent

post_text:
White Cloud Public School Families-

Many families are very impacted recently with loss of jobs, having their hours cut, and many other hardships. There is help available from the State of Michigan, and the process now has many less steps during these very trying times.

Visit www.michigan.gov/mibridges to apply online. If you are not able to apply online, call 689-5500 (the DHHS office number in White Cloud) to have an application mailed to you or to see if there are applications you can pick up outside of their lobby since their lobbies are closed.

Some other resources:

https://asdonthego.ku.edu/

https://consciousdiscipline.com/resources/why-cant-i-go-to-school-social-story/

https://afirm.fpg.unc.edu/supporting-individuals-autism-through-uncertain-times

https://www.npr.org/2020/03/24/820542927/how-to-talk-about-covid-19-with-people-who-have-autism

https://www.autismspeaks.org/news/how-cope-disrupted-family-routines-during-covid-19

Be safe. Seek help if your family is in need. Cherish your time with your family. WC Pride and WC Cares!

WCPS

Thank you, Thank you, Thank you to all who purchased tickets to help the junior class meet their goal of selling 1000 raffle tickets. We sold a total of 1,146 raffle tickets.

Thank you to everyone who sold raffle tickets. There were 19 juniors, 13 seniors and 5 sophomores that sold tickets.

Thank you to the Lion's Den and Ray Williams for letting us borrow their tumbler.

Thank you to Mr. Canning for allowing this to try this new idea of a fundraiser and helping us succeed.

Now for the winners:

1st prize: Matt Rouhan, Lake Orion, Mi
2nd prize: Letha Foster, White Cloud, MI
3rd prize: Tim Perysian, Fremont, MI

It is amazing what this community will do for the school and our students. Thank you so much for all of your support.

Barb Peacock and Stephen Smith - Junior Class Advisers

At this time, we’d like to congratulate 11th grade quiz bowl co-captains Parker Karnes and Janessa Shepard for being selected this past week by the NAQT National Quiz Bowl Committee to compete in the 2020 National Quiz Bowl Championship for Individuals, which will be held in Chicago on April 5.
Based on nation-wide quiz bowl statistics compiled by NAQT, both Parker and Janessa rank as 2 of the best quiz bowl players in the United States with Classes A, B, C, and D combined. Parker is the son of Joe and Stephanie Karnes, and Janessa is the daughter of Ed and Melinda Shepard.
Congratulations to both of you and your parents!
WC PRIDE!!!!

For 31 years, the MHSAA and Farm Bureau Insurance have honored the best student-athletes in Michigan. Again this year they will award 32 students with $1,000 scholarships based on achievement and leadership in athletics and activities, as well as responses to short-answer and essay questions. In many ways, this is the most prestigious honor the MHSAA awards annually.
Olivia Bowman has been selected as a finalist for the MHSAA Scholar-Athlete Award.
Olivia is a 3-sport athlete, participating in volleyball, basketball, and softball. She is involved in many school and community activities. She has recently been named the valedictorian of the class of 2020.
WC PRIDE!!!

Winners will be competing in the next level of competition soon. Good luck!

post_text:
White Cloud Community-

We have been monitoring our K-12 building's student attendance for the past few days. Due to a large number of students out with the flu and/or fever, White Cloud Public Schools will be closed Thursday, January 30 & Friday, January 31 for the health and the safety of our students and staff. We will be utilizing our cleaning crews and transportation department to properly disinfect all touch-points in buildings and buses during this time.

School will resume on Monday, February 3, 2020, and we look forward to everyone getting healthy.

WCPS thanks you for your understanding. WC PRIDE!!!!

Ed Canning
Superintendent

We had a great time at STEAM Challenge. The theme was Carnival. Students were able to play carnival games and have cotton candy, sno cones, and popcorn.

I am incredibly proud of our students. They came in the REACH room during lunch/recess to finish their candy Ferris wheel. The Ferris wheel had to turn all the way at least once. They took home first place in the elementary division. We also had a team competition based on teamwork and product. Groups consisted of students from different school districts. Attached are some pictures from the event.

The students were represented White Cloud and White Cloud REACH very well. 😊

post_text: The White Cloud Jr. High again placed in all STEAM Challenge Events. We competed against eight other schools. This year's theme was Carnival. Competing Schools were from Newaygo, Oceana, Lake, and Muskegon Counties. We took 1st place in three different areas: The Art Challenge (Hazel Slocum, Veronica Eagle, Adaleene Gordon and Rillie Heether) Open Art (Haley Deaton), Team Challenge Haley Deaton. Audrey Proctor placed 2nd in the Ferris Wheel Competition, while Courtney Plotts took 2nd in the Team Challenge. Henry Harmon took 3rd in the Roller Coaster Challenge. Congrats! White Cloud REACH for a such hard work and dedication.

post_text:
The WC High School student council is raising money to purchase a new drinking fountain to replace the old one in the upstairs hallway. In efforts to raise enough money, we are having a Penny Prince and Princess competition between the classes. How this works is there is a male and female representative from each class. We want to incorporate the community into our little competition. At the Snowcoming game tomorrow night against the Lakeview Wildcats we will have buckets set up near the concession stand where you will be able to vote. How the voting works is all coins are positive votes and bills are negative votes. We would love to have everyone participate.



Freshman: William Fehrlen and Gaby Reeve

Sophomore: Kobe Canning and Kyleah Baker

Junior: Sam Venema and Naomi Thompson

Senior: Devin Kakoczki and Jasmine Higgs

post_text: Ms. Wildfong’s 2nd grade class enjoyed fall STEM ( Science, Technology, Engineering and Math) activities and pumpkin math the past few weeks. Students were challenged to build a floating raft that would hold “people” (pennies) out of apple slices and wooden craft sticks. The winning raft held 33 pennies. Students also built candy towers out of candy, marshmallows and toothpicks. The tallest tower was 11 inches. Partners worked together to build wind-powered marble mazes out various materials. This task was much more difficult than it seems. Each activity required them to draw a blueprint prior to creating their piece and then document changes they made along the way to improve their creation. Last week small groups estimated the weight and circumference of a large pumpkin and then weighed and measured the pumpkin to see how accurate their estimation was. Students discussed the reasons pumpkins of the same size varied in weight from 22 to 29 pounds. Good things are happening at White Cloud Elementary!!
